<TITLE>Sad letdown for chess kids</TITLE>


<TEXT>
2 Views  0 Comment African Championship, Chess SA, Eastern Cape Schools Chess, Fungile Ngceka, Nomfusi Vusa, World Individual Championship 

Chess player Hlomisa Vusa is among one of several from the Eastern Cape who were not <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">invited</EVENT> to an open tournament in Zambia 

Picture: Brian Witbooi 

No tournament invitations despite <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">qualifying</EVENT> 

Angry parents are <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">blaming</EVENT> the Eastern Cape schools chess structure after their children, who qualified, did not <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">receive</EVENT> an invitation to an open tournament that <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">took</EVENT> place in Zambia <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="2016-12">last month</TIMEX3>. 

The parents  whose children were not able to <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">attend</EVENT> either the African Championship in Zambia or the World Individual Championship in Russia  <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">claimed</EVENT> a lack of communication was the biggest problem. 

The young qualifying players had a choice between the two events, with costs being the most differentiating factor and the African tournament being the less expensive. 

It is not known exactly how many children who <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">wished</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">attend</EVENT> but did not <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">receive</EVENT> invitations from the national chess body were affected because the national body relies on the regions to supply names. 

However, parent Nomfusi Vusa, 45, of Bridgemeade, <EVENT eid="e11" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> she had been <EVENT eid="e12" class="I_STATE">prepared</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">pay</EVENT> for her 15-year-old daughter Hlomisa to <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">attend</EVENT> the event in Zambia, but the problem was a lack of communication. 

We did not <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">receive</EVENT> any <EVENT eid="e16" class="I_ACTION">indication</EVENT> since Hlomisa <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">won</EVENT> in the U15 division <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="2016">last year</TIMEX3>, what the way forward would be, she <EVENT eid="e18" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>. 

When she <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">attended</EVENT> the [South African Winter Schools Chess Championship] tournament in Durban, they <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">went</EVENT> as a union and because of that I never <EVENT eid="e21" class="I_STATE">thought</EVENT> it <EVENT eid="e22" class="STATE">was</EVENT> my responsibility to <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">follow</EVENT> up. 

It is <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">frustrating</EVENT> because it was a glorious time after she <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">qualified</EVENT>. She even <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">received braiding</EVENT> on her school blazer because of this and then she was unable to <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">attend</EVENT> the <EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">tournament</EVENT> in Zambia, Vusa <EVENT eid="e29" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>. 

She <EVENT eid="e30" class="REPORTING">added</EVENT> that her daughter had <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">spent</EVENT> most of her time preparing for the Zambia tournament but ended up <EVENT eid="e32" class="OCCURRENCE">attending</EVENT> the local championship in Boksburg instead. 

Nicole Peter, 34, of Humewood, whose sons Neathan, 9, and Noah, 7, qualified because they were among the top 22 players in the country, <EVENT eid="e33" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> they had not <EVENT eid="e34" class="OCCURRENCE">received</EVENT> invitations either. 

There are huge communication gaps in the Eastern Cape, Peter <EVENT eid="e35" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>.
</TEXT>


